      The principal sits in a pivotal position to set the tone of the school for the students, teachers, parents, and community. They understand curriculum and know what is happening in the classrooms. They stay current on emerging curriculums essential to the success of their students and how to integrate important change into classroom learning. The twenty-first century has revealed essential life skills necessary for success in nearly every area of employment.
      <br />
      <br />
      <img src="images/principal.jpg" style="float: left; margin: 0 0 0 0; padding: 15px 15px 45px 0;" alt="Principal helping student" />
      Kids in today's America are global citizens - even in small town America. Students must be globally literate, sensitive to many cultures and world wide disasters and devastations. Today a premium is placed on creative and innovative thinking. Through cooperative and collaborative thinking, crossing curriculum disciplines, major breakthroughs are achieved.
      Much that is created in medicine and industry is accomplished by large teams emphasizing communication skills and the ability to work together. Many believe EQ is as important as IQ and essential to the survival of a nation and success of our students.
      <br />
      <br />
      The Key Life Skills include: integrity, cooperation, responsibility, communication, initiative, perseverance, organizing, interpersonal skills, service, and problem solving, The skills are caught more frequently than taught. The Integrated Spelling and Writing Program incorporates many activities that provide students experience for developing these vital life skills. Cooperative group and team learning activities give students opportunities to develop many of the skills. Projects are included for total class involvement with planning, organizing and carrying out service to others.
